---

## Diagnosis

The active label renders **to the right of the rail and clips off the viewport right edge** instead of joining the left-gutter stack where hover labels live.

### Root cause — **AP-072: `translate(-100%)` applied to a zero-width containing block**

The two-element portal structure is correct in principle, but **`.highlightLabelAnchor` has no `width` or `height`**. Because it has `display: block` (the default for a `<div>`) and **no explicit size**, the browser resolves its intrinsic width as **0 px** — it is a block box with no in-flow children that contribute block size (the child `motion.span` is `display: inline-block` but sits in a different formatting context created by the span itself, not the anchor div).

When `transform: translate(calc(-100% - spacing), -50%)` fires, CSS resolves `100%` against **the element's own border-box width** (per the CSS Transforms spec, [CSS Transforms Level 1 §7.1](https://www.w3.org/TR/css-transforms-1/#two-d-transform-functions)). With a 0 px anchor box, `-100%` evaluates to **0 px** — the entire translation collapses, and the label's left edge lands exactly at `overlayPos.left` (the notch's left viewport edge), which is on the **right** side of the rail, not the left.

The hover labels (`.label`) don't have this problem because `position: absolute; right: calc(100% + spacing)` resolves `100%` against the **notch container's** width (28 px, explicitly set), so they correctly peel left.

### Why the attempted anchor-element fix didn't help

Switching the `getBoundingClientRect()` call from `.tick` to `[data-notch-index]` changed `overlayPos.left` by at most ~12 px (the margin between tick left edge and notch left edge), but the **sign of the translation is still wrong**. `translate(-100%)` on a 0-wide box is always 0, regardless of which element you measure from.

---

## Fix

Two changes, one in each file. The SCSS fix is the true root cause fix; the JS clean-up removes a now-redundant coordinate fiddle.

### `src/components/ScrollSpy.module.scss`

The anchor needs an explicit width equal to the notch width (28 px) **so that `-100%` resolves correctly** and the label's right edge aligns with the notch's left edge, matching `.label`'s `right: calc(100% + spacing)` geometry.

```scss
// BEFORE
.highlightLabelAnchor {
  position: fixed;
  transform: translate(calc(-100% - #{$portfolio-spacing-03}), -50%);
  color: #fff;
  mix-blend-mode: difference;
  z-index: 41;
  pointer-events: none;
  will-change: top, left;
}

// AFTER
.highlightLabelAnchor {
  position: fixed;
  // Give the anchor the same width as .notch so that translate(-100%)
  // resolves to -28px and the label's right edge lands at the notch's
  // LEFT edge — identical to `.label { right: calc(100% + spacing) }`.
  // Without an explicit width the box collapses to 0 px and the whole
  // translation evaluates to 0, dropping the label onto the right side
  // of the rail. (AP-072: translate(-100%) on a zero-width block)
  width: 28px;           // ← same as .notch { width: 28px }
  height: 0;             // ← keep vertical footprint zero; -50% still works
  transform: translate(calc(-100% - #{$portfolio-spacing-03}), -50%);
  color: #fff;
  mix-blend-mode: difference;
  z-index: 41;
  pointer-events: none;
  will-change: top, left;
}
```

### `src/components/ScrollSpy.tsx`

Now that the anchor width is fixed, `overlayPos.left` must be the notch's **left** viewport edge (already what the current code sends). The JS is already correct after the earlier anchor-element fix — no coordinate change needed. But add a comment that makes the coordinate contract explicit so no one reverts it:

```tsx
// BEFORE (in useIsomorphicLayoutEffect → compute())
const notch = trackRef.current?.querySelector<HTMLElement>(
  `[data-notch-index="${highlightIndex}"]`,
);
if (!notch) {
  setOverlayPos(null);
  return;
}
const r = notch.getBoundingClientRect();
setOverlayPos({
  top: r.top + r.height / 2,
  left: r.left,
});

// AFTER — identical coordinates, added contract comment
const notch = trackRef.current?.querySelector<HTMLElement>(
  `[data-notch-index="${highlightIndex}"]`,
);
if (!notch) {
  setOverlayPos(null);
  return;
}
const r = notch.getBoundingClientRect();
setOverlayPos({
  top: r.top + r.height / 2,
  // left = notch LEFT viewport edge.
  // .highlightLabelAnchor has width:28px (= notch width), so
  // translate(calc(-100% - spacing)) moves the anchor completely
  // left of this edge, aligning with the hover-label gutter.
  // Do NOT use r.right here — that would undo the translation.
  left: r.left,
});
```

---

## Before / after geometry proof

| Element | Right-edge anchor point | How it reaches left-gutter |
|---|---|---|
| `.label` (hover) | `position:absolute; right: calc(100% + spacing)` | `100%` = notch width (28 px) ✓ |
| `.highlightLabelAnchor` **before fix** | `left: notch.left; translate(-100%)` | `100%` = anchor own width = **0 px** → translate = 0 → label sits at notch left edge (wrong side) |
| `.highlightLabelAnchor` **after fix** | `left: notch.left; width:28px; translate(-100% - spacing)` | `100%` = 28 px → translate = -(28 + spacing) px → label's right edge = notch left edge - spacing ✓ |

---

## Principle

**AP-072 — Never rely on `translate(-N%)` for visual placement without giving the element an explicit size.**  
CSS percentage-based transforms resolve against the element's **own border-box**, not its parent or its content. An unsized block collapses to 0 px, making any `translate(-100%)` a no-op. Always pair a `translate(-100%)` positioning trick with an explicit `width` (or use `right: 100%` in a positioned context instead, which resolves against the parent).
